            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I do not think this should be treated as a `vim.system()` bug.\n\nWhen I added `vim.system()`, the intent was a small wrapper around `vim.uv.spawn()` with convenient stdin/stdout/stderr handling.\n\nIn this issue, `vim.system()` starts `bash`. `bash` then creates a pipeline. Killing the process Nvim spawned and killing every descendant that process may create are different contracts. `SystemObj:kill()` currently means \"signal the spawned process\", not \"recursively clean up a process tree\".\n\nI understand the argument that `kill()` should default to killing children too, because that is often what users mean by \"stop this job\". But I do not think that is a feasible default for this API. To guarantee that behavior, Nvim has to either create an ownership boundary up front, such as a Unix process group, or discover descendants later. Both choices have unavoidable tradeoffs.\n\nUnix process semantics are not Windows process semantics. Unix has signals, process groups, sessions, and `setsid()`. Windows has different process handles and termination behavior. Making every `vim.system()` process detached/process-group-led may help with group termination on Unix, but it changes lifecycle behavior if Nvim exits or crashes. Enumerating descendants after the fact is racy and platform-specific. Mapping Unix signal behavior onto Windows is not clean either.\n\nThis is why I do not think `vim.system()` should grow job-control policy defaults. It exposes process-shaped details like `pid`, `kill(signal)`, and `code`/`signal` results. Once the API exposes those, it is already asking callers to think in terms of the underlying process model.\n\nA real high-level job-control API would need to abstract over those details, including PIDs, process groups, signals, exit status, and what termination even means on each platform. If the API still revolves around PIDs and signal-like behavior, then it is leaking the underlying process model rather than abstracting it.\n\nSo I think the better fix is documentation, not changing the abstraction. We should be clear that `SystemObj:kill()` targets the spawned process and does not guarantee descendant cleanup. If there is a genuine portability bug in the low-level spawn behavior, that belongs in `vim.uv`/libuv or the platform layer, not in `vim.system()` growing its own partial job-control model.\n",
