        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@lewis6991 \n\n> Making every `vim.system()` process detached/process-group-led may help with group termination on Unix, but it changes lifecycle behavior if Nvim exits or crashes.\n\nIn short, the \"lifecyle behavior\" is functionally identical, with or without `detach`.  The existing behavior is that nothing will be terminated as a result of neovim exiting/crashing.\n\nIn detail, all that POSIX specifies that is applicable here is that if a process group becomes orphaned, and contains at least one stopped process, then the entire process group is sent `SIGHUP` (to know that they've been orphaned, by default the process will terminate) followed by `SIGCONT` (so that the stopped process(es) can react to the `SIGHUP`). \n\nIn that fringe case, the behavior will indeed differ, but in my opinion it's generally more consistent.\n\n>Both choices have unavoidable tradeoffs.\n\nThere's no real tradeoff. I think you may have been misled by uv's documentation. The process will \"will keep running after the parent process exits\" no matter what because the neovim server process always creates a new session, presumably for the purpose of daemonizing. \n\nFor it to be the case that anything at all is removed on exit, there would need to be a centralized job control layer (as proposed by @justinmk) that keeps tracks of jobs and handles terminating them (by sending `SIGHUP`) upon neovim's exit.\n\nI should add that the most correct solution would be for neovim to only create a new process group for the spawned process, like a shell does, instead of creating a new session, but it's not possible with `uv_spawn`.\n\n---\n\n> I understand the argument that `kill()` should default to killing children too, because that is often what users mean by \"stop this job\".\n\nIt's not just what users expect, but the behavior POSIX intends as well. Job control in POSIX is defined entirely in terms of process groups, even in the case I described above the processes are handled together as a group. It is simply the idiomatic behavior on unix-likes. \n\n---\n\nThe intention of my PR is simply to make `vim.system` match `jobstart`'s behavior on unix-likes. They have basically the same interface and in my opinion it's clear that `vim.system` is the one misbehaving. ",
