            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I think the important distinction is between three separate policies:\n\n- process topology: whether Nvim creates a separate process group/session for the child;\n- kill policy: whether `SystemObj:kill()` targets only the spawned process or the whole group/tree;\n- ownership: whether Nvim stops the process during teardown.\n\n#39562 bundles topology and kill policy together for all Unix `vim.system()` calls. That changes the default shape of processes started by `vim.system()`, and makes `SystemObj:kill()` mean \"kill the process group\" rather than \"signal the spawned process\".\n\nThat default topology change can also break callers that run Nvim as part of a supervised process group. If a supervisor cancels Nvim's process group, children that `vim.system()` moved into a separate session/process group may no longer receive that cancellation. `jobstart()` can use this topology because it also has teardown ownership: non-detached jobs are stopped by Nvim when Nvim exits. `vim.system()` does not currently have that ownership path, so copying only the topology/kill part is much riskier.\n\nI think tree/job-control semantics should be explicit and backwards compatible. One way to do that is to introduce a `mode` option which describes the lifecycle contract:\n\n```lua\nvim.system(cmd)                         -- mode = 'process'\nvim.system(cmd, { mode = 'process' })   -- current behavior\nvim.system(cmd, { mode = 'job' })       -- owned job-control\nvim.system(cmd, { mode = 'detached' })  -- detached job-control\n```\n\nProposed semantics:\n\n- `mode = 'process'`:\n  - default;\n  - current `vim.system()` behavior;\n  - no forced new process group/session;\n  - `SystemObj:kill()` signals only the spawned process;\n  - Nvim does not own process-tree cleanup on exit.\n- `mode = 'job'`:\n  - `jobstart()`-style owned job;\n  - internally, Unix can still use `UV_PROCESS_DETACHED`/`setsid()` so the child gets its own process group;\n  - `SystemObj:kill()` stops the process group/tree;\n  - Nvim stops the job during teardown.\n- `mode = 'detached'`:\n  - `SystemObj:kill()` stops the process group/tree;\n  - Nvim does not stop it automatically when Nvim exits.\n\nThe existing `detach` option can be deprecated in favor of `mode=detached`. Mixing `mode` and `detach` should be rejected.\n\nThis keeps existing `vim.system()` callers compatible and gives users an explicit way to request `jobstart()`-style semantics.",
